{"parse":{"title":"mare","pageid":8864,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"mare\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==English==\n[[File:Lovely Little Girl.jpg|thumb|A mare]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/mɛə/|a=RP}}\n* {{IPA|en|/mɛɚ/|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-mare.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/meː/|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/meə/|a=NZ,non-near-square}}\n* {{IPA|en|/miə/|a=NZ,near-square}}\n* {{IPA|en|/meɹ/|a=Scotland}}\n* {{IPA|en|/mɜː(ɹ)/|a=Lancashire,square-nurse}}\n* {{homophones|en|mere<aa:near-square>||myrrh<aa:square-nurse>}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛə(ɹ)|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|mare}}, {{m|enm|meare}}, {{m|enm|meir}}, {{m|enm|mer}}, {{m|enm|mere}}, {{m|enm|meyre}}, {{m|enm|mure}}, from {{inh|en|ang|mīere|t=female horse, mare}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*marhijā}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*marhijō|t=female horse}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*marhaz|t=horse}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*márkos|t=horse}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|mere|t=mare}}, {{cog|stq|Märe|t=mare}}, {{cog|fy|merje|t=mare}}, {{cog|nl|merrie|t=mare}}, {{cog|de|Mähre|t=female horse}}, {{cog|da|mær|t=old mare}}, {{cog|fo|mer|t=mare}}, {{cog|is|meri|t=mare}}, {{cog|nb,nn|merr|t=mare}}, {{cog|sv|mæhr}}, {{m|sv|mær}}, {{m|sv|mähr}}, {{m|sv|märr|t=mare}}; also {{cog|br|marc'h|t=horse}}, {{cog|kw|margh|t=horse}}, {{cog|ga,gd|marc|t=horse}}, {{cog|cy|march|t=horse}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|meare||obsolete}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q1104034}}An adult [[female]] [[horse]].\n#: {{ant|en|stallion|stud|gelding}}\n#* {{RQ:Jefferies Amateur Poacher|chapter=1|passage=But then I had the [massive] flintlock by me for protection. ¶{{...}}The linen-press and a chest on the top of it formed, however, a very good gun-carriage; and, thus mounted, aim could be taken out of the window at the old '''mare''' feeding in the meadow below by the brook, and a 'bead' could be drawn upon Molly, the dairymaid, kissing the fogger behind the hedge,{{nb...}}.}}\n# {{lb|en|UK|Irish|pejorative|slang}} A [[foolish]] [[woman]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007|author=Hester Browne|title=Little Lady, Big Apple|passage=The silly '''mare''' phoned your mother, talking about applying for a mortgage, and we don't want that, do we?}}\n\n=====Coordinate terms=====\n{{col|en\n|foal<t:young horse>\n|colt<t:young male horse>\n|filly<t:young female horse>\n|pony<t:small horse>\n}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|Premarin|seamare|brood mare\n|flying mare\n|mare's fart\n|mare's leg\n|mare's milk\n|mare's nest\n|Mares Run\n|mare's tail\n|mare's teat\n|ride the three-legged mare\n|shanks' mare\n|stud mare\n|the grey mare is the better horse\n|Three-legged mare\n|three-legged mare\n|two-legged mare\n|wooden mare\n|Mare's Fart\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|female horse}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|аҽа́н}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|pelë|f}}\n* Andi: {{tt|ani|ича}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|حِجْر|f}}, {{tt|ar|فَرَس|f}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|فرس|f|tr=faras}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{tt|ary|عودة|f|tr=ʕawda}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|մատակ}}, {{tt+|hy|զամբիկ}}\n* Aromanian: {{tt|rup|iapã|f}}\n* Asturian: {{tt+|ast|yegua|f}}, {{tt+|ast|burra}}\n* Avar: {{tt|av|гӏала}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|madyan}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|бейә}}\n* Basque: {{tt+|eu|behor}}\n* Bats: {{t|bbl|ჴადალ}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|кабы́ла|f}}\n* Breton: {{tt+|br|kazeg|f}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|коби́ла|f}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|မြင်းမ}}\n* Buryat: {{tt|bua|гүүн}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|euga|f}}, {{tt+|ca|egua|f}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|кхаьл}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|騍馬|tr=kèmǎ}}, {{tt+|cmn|母馬|tr=mǔmǎ}}\n* Chuvash: {{tt|cv|кӗсре}}\n* Crimean Tatar: {{tt|crh|baytal}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|klisna|f}}, {{tt+|cs|kobyla|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|hoppe|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|merrie|f}}\n* East Yugur: {{tt|yuy|gün}}\n* Erzya: {{tt|myv|эльде}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt|eo|ĉevalino}}\n* Fala: {{t|fax|egua|f}} {{q|Lagarteiru, Mañegu}}, {{t|fax|yegua|f}} {{q|Mañegu, Valverdeñu}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|ryssa|f}}, {{tt|fo|mer|f}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|tamma}}\n* Franco-Provençal: {{tt|frp|èga|f}}, {{tt|frp|cavala|f}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|jument|f}}\n* Frisian:\n*: North Frisian: {{tt|frr|Ök}} {{qualifier|Sylt}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|egua|f}}, {{tt|gl|egoa|f}}, {{tt+|gl|besta|f}}, {{tt|gl|brégola|f}}, {{tt+|gl|faca|f}}, {{tt|gl|facaneia|f}}, {{tt|gl|marzoa|f}}\n* Georgian: {{tt+|ka|ფაშატი}}, {{tt|ka|ჭაკი}}, {{tt|ka|ხრდალი}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Stute|f}}, {{qualifier|obsolete}} {{tt+|de|Mähre|f}}, {{tt|de|Pferdeweibchen|n}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|φοράδα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{tt|grc|ἵππος|f}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{tt-check|gug|[[kavaju]] [[kuña]]}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt|he|סוסה|f|tr=susá|alt=סוסה / סוּסָה}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|घोड़ी|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|kanca}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|hryssa|f}}, {{tt|is|meri|f}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|kavalino}}\n* Ingush: {{tt|inh|кхал}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt|ia|cavalla}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|láir|f}}\n*: Old Irish: {{tt|sga|láir|f}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|cavalla|f}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|牝馬|tr={{lang|ja|ひんば}}, hinba}}\n* Kabuverdianu: {{tt|kea|égua}}\n* Kalmyk: {{tt-check|xal|кӗсре|alt=гүн}}\n* Kazakh: {{tt|kk|бие}}\n* Khakas: {{tt|kjh|пии}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|암말}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t+|ckb|مایین}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|mahîn|f}}, {{tt+|kmr|mehîn|f}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{tt+|ky|бээ}}\n* Lao: {{t-needed|lo}}\n* Latgalian: {{tt|ltg|kēve|f}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|equa|f}}\n* Latvian: {{tt+|lv|ķēve|f}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt+|lt|kumelė|f}}\n* Low German:\n*: German Low German: {{tt|nds-de|Tööt|f}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|ко́била|f}}\n* Malay: {{tt|ms|kuda betina}}, {{tt|ms|kuda betina dewasa}}\n* Maltese: {{tt|mt|debba|f}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|hoiho uwha}}, {{tt|mi|hōiho uha}}\n* Megleno-Romanian: {{t|ruq|iapă|f}}\n* Mongolian: {{tt+|mn|гүү}}\n* Navajo: {{tt|nv|łį́į́tsaʼii}}\n* Norman: {{tt|nrf|jeunment|f}} {{qualifier|Jersey}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|hoppe|m|f}}, {{tt+|no|merr|m|f}}, {{tt|no|hunnhest|m}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|hoppe|f}}, {{tt|nn|merr|f}}, {{tt|nn|hohest|m}}\n* Occitan: {{tt+|oc|èga|f}}, {{tt+|oc|cavala|f}}\n* Old Church Slavonic: {{tt|cu|кобꙑла|f}}\n* Old English: {{tt|ang|mīere|f}}\n* Old Norse: {{tt|non|hryssa|f}}, {{tt|non|merr|f}}, {{tt|non|jalda|f}}\n* Ossetian: {{tt|os|ефс}}\n* Pashto: {{tt+|ps|اسپه|f|tr=aspa}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|مادیان|tr=mâdiyân}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{tt|pdt|Kobbel|f}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|klacz|f}}, {{tt+|pl|kobyła|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|égua|f}}\n* Punjabi: {{tt+|pa|ਘੋੜੀ|f}}\n* Romani: {{tt|rom|grasni|f}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|iapă|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|кобы́ла|f}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|meir}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|làir|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|ко̀била|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|kòbila}}\n* Shor: {{tt|cjs|пей}}\n* Sikkimese: {{t|sip|རྒོདམ}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|kobyla|f}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|kobíla|f}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{tt|dsb|kobyła|f}}\n*: Upper Sorbian: {{tt|hsb|kobła|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|yegua|f}}, {{t+|es|jaca|f}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|märr|c}}, {{tt+|sv|sto|n}}\n* Tajik: {{tt+|tg|модиён}}\n* Taos: {{tt|twf|yàwoʼóna}}\n* Tatar: {{tt+|tt|бия}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|ఆడగుర్రం}}, {{tt+|te|బడబ}}\n* Thai: {{t-needed|th}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|kısrak}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{tt|ota|قیصراق|tr=kısrak}}, {{tt|ota|یوند|tr=yund}}\n* Tuvan: {{tt|tyv|бе}}, {{tt|tyv|кызырак}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|коби́ла|f}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|بايتال}}, {{t|ug|بىيە}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|biya}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t|vi|[[ngựa]] [[cái]]}}\n* Vilamovian: {{tt|wym|köwuł}}\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|jijevod}}, {{tt|vo|jijeval}} {{qualifier|obsolete}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|cavale|f}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|caseg|f}}\n* Wolof: {{tt|wo|wajan|alt=wajan wi}}\n* Yakut: {{tt|sah|биэ}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*mer-|id=die}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|mare|id=spirit}}, from {{inh|en|ang|mare||nightmare, monster}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*marā}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*marǭ||nightmare, incubus}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*mor-||feminine evil spirit}}. {{doublet|en|mara}}.\n\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nAkin to Dutch (dial.) {{m|nl|mare}}, German (dial.) {{m|de|Mahr}}, {{cog|non|mara}} ( > {{cog|da|mare}}, {{cog|sv|mara||incubus, nightmare}}; also {{cog|sga|Morrígan||phantom queen}}, {{cog|sq|merë||horror}}, {{cog|pl|zmora||nightmare}}, {{cog|cs|mura||nightmare, moth}}, {{cog|el|Μόρα}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/mɛə/|a=British}}\n* {{IPA|en|/mɛɚ/|a=US}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-mare.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛə(ɹ)|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|mayor|qq1=in a number of dialects}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|evil spirit}} {{lb|en|obsolete|or|historical}} A type of evil [[spirit]] formerly thought to sit on the chest of a sleeping person; also, the feeling of suffocation felt during sleep, attributed to such a spirit.\n# {{lb|en|UK|Ireland|Commonwealth|colloquial}} A [[nightmare]]; a frustrating or terrible experience.\n#: {{ux|en|I'm having a complete '''mare''' today.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|daymare}}\n* {{l|en|nightmare}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|evil spirit}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|зъл дух|m-p}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|můra|f}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|mare}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|painajainen}}, {{tt+|fi|mara}}, {{tt|fi|ajajainen}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Mahr|m|f}}, {{tt+|de|Alb|m}}, {{tt|de|Nachtalb|m}}, {{tt+|de|Drude|m}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|mara}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|incubo|m}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|mara}}\n* Old Norse: {{t|non|mara}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|mara|f}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|mora|f}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|mara|c}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|frustrating or terrible experience}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|painajainen}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|incubo|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*mer- (sea)}}\nBorrowed from {{bor|en|la|mare||sea}}. {{doublet|en|maar|mere<t:a body of standing water>}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈmɑɹ.eɪ/|/ˈmɛɚ.i/|/ˈmɑɹ.i/|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑɹi|s=2}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|maria}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|plain}}{{lb|en|planetology}} A large, dark [[plain]], which may have the appearance of a [[sea]], such as those on the [[Moon]].\n# {{lb|en|planetology}} On [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Titan]], any of several [[lake]]s which are large [[expanse]]s of what is thought to be [[liquid]] [[hydrocarbon]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|[[Kraken Mare|Kraken '''Mare''']] (a lake of liquid hydrocarbons on Titan which is slightly larger than the [[Caspian Sea]])}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|planetology: dark circular plain}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|月海|tr=jyut6 hoi2}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|月海|tr=yuèhǎi}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|meri}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Mare|n}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt+|id|mare}}, {{t+|id|maria}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|mare|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|mar|m}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|мо́ре|n}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|deniz}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt|vi|biển Mặt Trăng}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nSee {{m|en|mayor}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{obsolete form of|en|mayor}}.\n# {{obsolete form of|en|mair}}.\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aemr|mera|Amer.|rame|mear|Erma|Maer|Mera|Ream|amer.|Arem|arme|ramé|ream}}\n\n{{topics|en|Mythological creatures}}\n{{cln|en|heteronyms|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{C|en|Female animals|Horses}}\n\n==Afar==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{aa-IPA|maré}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{aa-noun|maré|g=f|sg=maréyta|gsg=m|sg2=mareytá|gsg2=f}}\n\n# [[family]], [[relationship]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{aa-decl|maré}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{aa-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|aa|Northern Afar|intransitive}} [[live]]\n# {{lb|aa|Northern Afar|intransitive}} [[continue]]\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{aa-conj/II|m|a|r|á}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|aa|mára||people}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:aa:Parker:1985|+}}\n* {{R:aa:Hassan Kamil:2015}}\n\n==Albanian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|sq|marë|marulë}}\n\n===Etymology===\nPlurale tantum; plural of variant {{m|sq|marë}}, borrowed through {{bor|sq|VL.|-}} from {{bor|sq|la|marum||cat thyme, kind of sage}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{sq-noun|f||marja}}\n\n# [[strawberry tree]] ({{taxfmt|Arbutus unedo|species}})\n# strawberry tree fruit\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sq|mareshtë}}\n\n{{C|sq|Ericales order plants}}\n\n==Aromanian==\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|rup|adjective}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|rup|mari}}\n\n==Catalan==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|ca|roa-oca|mare}}, from {{inh|ca|la|mater|māter, mātrem}}, from {{inh|ca|itc-pro|*mātēr}}, from {{inh|ca|ine-pro|*méh₂tēr}}. Compare {{cog|oc|maire}}, {{cog|fr|mère}}, {{cog|es|madre}}, {{cog|it|madre}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ca-IPA}}\n* {{audio|ca|LL-Q7026 (cat)-Millars-mare.wav|a=Valencia}}\n* {{rhymes|ca|aɾe|s=2}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ca-noun|f}}\n\n# [[mother]]\n#: {{uxi|ca|'''mare''' subrogada|surrogate '''mother'''}}\n# [[uterus]] {{q|of an animal}}\n#: {{syn|ca|úter}}\n# {{lb|ca|by analogy}} main [[course]] of a [[river]] or [[canal]]; [[channel]]\n# {{lb|ca|Mallorca|playground games}} [[home]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|ca\n|cèl·lula mare\n|Dia de la Mare\n|emmarat\n|marededeu\n}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ca:IEC2}}\n* {{R:ca:GDLC}}\n* {{R:ca:DNV}}\n* {{R:ca:DCVB}}\n\n{{C|ca|Female family members}}\n\n==Central Bikol==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{hyph|bcl|ma|re}}\n* {{bcl-IPA}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|bcl|verb|head=máre}}\n\n# {{missp|bcl|mari}}\n\n==Corsican==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|co|mari}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|co|la|mare}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|co|/ma.re/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|co|noun|g=m}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:INFCOR}}\n\n==Danish==\n{{wp|+ (folklore)}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|da|non|mara}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|da|/ˈmɑːɑ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{da-noun|n|r}}\n\n# {{lb|da|folklore}} a {{l|en|mare|id=evil spirit}} {{gloss|an evil spirit}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{da-noun-infl|n|r}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|da|mareridt|g=n}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Den Danske Ordbog}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-mare.ogg}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|nl|gem-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|nl|dum|mare|mâre}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|mari|māri}}, from {{inh|nl|gmw-pro|*mārī||story}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nl-noun|f|-en|++}}\n\n# {{lb|nl|Belgium|archaic}} [[message]], [[report]], [[story]]\n#: {{syn|nl|bericht|tijding|verslag|verhaal}}\n# {{lb|nl|archaic}} [[rumor]]\n#: {{syn|nl|gerucht}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|nl|vermaren}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nProbably from {{der|nl|ML.|mara||standing water}}, from {{der|nl|la|mare||sea}}. {{doublet|de|Maar|Meer}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nl-noun|f|-en|++}}\n\n# depression in non-volcanic stone\n#: {{coord|nl|maar}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|nl|dum|mare|māre|incubus}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|*mara}}, from {{inh|nl|gmw-pro|*marā}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*marǭ}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nl-noun|f|-s|++}}\n\n# a [[nocturnal]] [[monster]] or [[spirit]] that torments its victims while they are sleeping\n# {{lb|nl|Belgium}} [[nightmare]]\n# [[witch]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nl|nachtmare}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|nl|maretak}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nl|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nl|maren||s|pres|sub}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|nl|arme}}, {{l|nl|rame}}\n\n==Finnish==\n\n===Etymology===\nCompare {{m|fi|mairea}}, {{m|fi|kare|id=wave}}, perhaps a {{lg|blend}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fi-p|*}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fi-noun}}\n\n# {{tlb|fi|dated|or|dialectal}} (slight, faint) [[smile]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{fi-decl-hame|mar|||a}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|fr|frm|mare}}, from {{inh|fr|fro|mare}}, from {{der|fr|non|marr||lake, sea, pool}}, from {{der|fr|gem-pro|*mari||lake, sea}}, from {{der|fr|ine-pro|*móri}}. {{doublet|fr|mer}} inherited from Latin.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|mâre}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-mare.ogg}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-mare.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-mare.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|f}}\n\n# [[puddle]]\n# [[pool]]\n#* {{RQ:Flaubert Bovary|passage= La cour allait en montant; plantée d'arbres symétriquement espacés, et le bruit gai d'un troupeau d'oies retentissait près de la '''mare'''.}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fr|pavé dans la mare}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|fr|amer}}\n* {{l|fr|arme}}, {{l|fr|armé}}\n* {{l|fr|rame}}, {{l|fr|ramé}}\n\n==Indonesian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{learned borrowing|id|la|mare||sea}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{id-pr|rhyme=0}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{id-noun|head=marê}}\n\n# {{lb|id|planetology}} {{l|en|mare}} {{gl|a large, dark plain, which may have the appearance of a sea, such as those on the Moon}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|id|maria}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:KBBI Daring}}\n\n==Istriot==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|ist|la|mare}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|ist|noun}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n#* {{quote-book|ist|year=1877|author=Antonio Ive|title=Canti popolari istriani: raccolti a Rovigno|volume=5|publisher=Ermanno Loescher|page=99\n|passage=Cume li va puleîto in alto '''mare'''!\n|translation=How they row well on the high '''seas'''!}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|ist|alto mare}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|ist|la|mater|māter}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|ist|noun|g=f}}\n\n# [[mother]]\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|ist|mama}}\n\n==Italian==\n{{wp|it:}}\n[[Image:Sea-chile.jpg|thumb|right]]\n[[Image:Korea-Busan-Duseong peninsula-01.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|it|mar||apocopic}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|it|la|mare}}, from {{inh|it|itc-pro|*mari}}, from {{inh|it|ine-pro|*móri}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr|^à<audio:It-mare.ogg><audio:It-il mare.ogg;Audio (''il mare'')>}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|m|adj=marittimo,marino}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col|it\n|ammarare\n|frutto di mare\n|lupo di mare\n|marea\n|mareggiata\n|maremoto\n|maretta\n|marina\n|marinaio\n|marinara\n|marinare\n|marittimo\n}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col|it\n|oceano<t:ocean>\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:it:Collins}}\n* {{R:it:Trec}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|it|a=aemr|Mera|arme|erma|mera|rame|rema}}\n\n{{C|it|Bodies of water|Landforms}}\n\n==Japanese==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{ja-romaji}}\n\n# {{ja-romanization of|まれ}}\n\n==Latin==\n{{wp|la:}}\n[[Image:Beach View 0.jpg|thumb|right|mare]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{la-IPA}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|la|id=sea|:inh|itc-pro:*mari<id:sea>}}\nFrom {{inh|la|itc-pro|*mari}}, from {{inh|la|ine-pro|*móri}}.<ref>{{R:itc:EDL|page=365|head=mare}}</ref>\n\n====Noun====\n{{la-noun|mare<3>}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n#* {{Q|la|Gnaeus Naevius|Bellum Punicum|notes=fragment in Priscian, ''Institutiones Grammaticae'', 7, ''De genetivo plurali tertiae declinationis''|quote=Neptunum regnatorem '''marum'''|t=Neptune, ruler '''of the seas'''}}\n#* {{Q|la|Julius Caesar|De Bello Gallico|5|1|quote=[facit...] ad onera ac multitudinem iumentorum transportandam paulo latiores quam quibus in reliquis utimur '''maribus'''.|t=In order to transport cargo and beasts of burden, he [Julius Caesar] had them made a little wider than the ones we use in other '''seas'''.}}\n#* {{Q|la|Roger Bacon|Secretum Secretorum|2|29 (De preparacione carnum viperarum sive serpentum et draconum)|year=13th c.|quote=Et oportet ut alienentur cornute et varie et aspides declines ad albedinem. Et non capiantur ex piscinis vel litoribus fluviorum et aquarum vel '''marium''', vel de petrosis, quoniam in eis sunt quercine, facientes sitim, immo capiantur in loco longinquo ab humorositate.}}\n#* {{Q|la|Joseph Pope, George Monro Grant|Canada's official motto|year=1921|quote=a '''marī''' usque ad '''mare'''|t=from '''sea''' to '''sea'''}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{la-ndecl|mare<3>|abl_sg=marī/mare|gen_pl=marium/marum}}\n* The genitive plural form {{m|la|marium}}, although regularly formed for an i-stem noun, is not attested in the corpus of classical texts. ''Marum'' is found only once, in a line from Gnaeus Naevius.\n* The 5th/6th-century grammarian [[w:Priscian|Priscian]] (''Institutiones'' 7) says it is rarely used in the genitive plural, noting Caesar's use of ''maribus'' too. Similarly, the 4th-century grammarian [[w:Flavius Sosipater Charisius|Charisius]] claims it lacks both a genitive plural *''marium'' and a *''maribus'' form (but see the quotation from Julius Caesar above): <blockquote>''\"maria\" tamen quamvis dicantur pluraliter, attamen nec \"marium\" nec \"maribus\" dicemus'' <br/>— although ''maria'' can be said in the plural, nevertheless we won't say ''marium'' nor ''maribus'' (''Ars'' 1.11).</blockquote>\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|la|pontus}}\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n{{col|la\n|Mare Aegaeum|Mare Balticum|Mare Germanicum|Mare Caribicum|Mare Caribaeum|Caspium mare|Mare Rubrum|Mare Mediterrāneum|Mare Nostrum|Mare Internum|Mare Ionium|Mare Hadriāticum|Tyrrhēnum mare\n}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|la\n|bimaris\n|Mare Hibērnicum\n|mariambulus\n|marīnus\n|maritimēnsis\n|maritimus\n|maritumus\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top3}}\n* Insular Romance:\n** {{desc|sc|mare|mari}}\n* Balkano-Romance:\n** {{desc|rup|amari|amare|mari}}\n** {{desc|ruo|måre}}\n** {{desc|ruq|mari}}\n** {{desc|ro|mare|g=f}}\n* Italo-Dalmatian:\n** {{desc|co|mare}}\n*** {{desc|sdn|mari}}\n*** {{desc|sdc|mari}}\n** {{desc|dlm|mur}}\n** {{desc|ist|mare}}\n** {{desc|it|mare}}\n** {{desc|nap|mare}}\n** {{desc|scn|mari}}\n** {{desc|vec|mar}}\n* Rhaeto-Romance:\n** {{desc|fur|mâr}}\n** {{desc|rm|mar|mer}}\n* Gallo-Italic:\n** {{desc|egl|mèr}}\n** {{desc|lij|mâ|mà}}\n** {{desc|lmo|mar}}\n** {{desc|pms|mar}}\n** {{desc|rgn|mêr}}\n* Gallo-Romance:\n** {{desc|roa-oca|mar}}\n*** {{desc|ca|mar|g=mf}}\n** {{desctree|fro|mer|g=f}}\n** {{desc|pro|mar}}\n*** {{desc|oc|mar|mer}}\n* Ibero-Romance:\n** {{desc|an|mar}}\n** {{desctree|roa-opt|mar|g=m}}\n** {{desc|roa-ole|*mar}}\n*** {{desc|ast|mar}}\n*** {{desc|ext|mari}}\n*** {{desc|mwl|mar}}\n** {{desc|osp|mar}}\n*** {{desc|lad|mar}}\n*** {{desctree|es|mar|g=mf}}\n* Borrowings:\n** {{desc|bor=1|en|mare}}\n** {{desctree|bor=1|eo|maro}}\n** {{desc|bor=1|ia|mar}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|la|noun form}}\n\n# {{infl of|la|mās||abl|s}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|la|adjective form}}\n\n# {{infl of|la|mās||nom//acc//voc|n|s}}\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n===Further reading===\n* [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059:entry=mare mare] in {{cite-book|author=Charlton T. Lewis and Charles Short|title=[[w:A Latin Dictionary|A Latin Dictionary]]|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|year=1879}}\n* [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0060:entry=mare mare] in {{cite-book|author=Charlton T. Lewis|title=An Elementary Latin Dictionary|publisher=Harper & Brothers|location=New York|year=1891}}\n<!--* {{R:M&A}}-->\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|la|mera}}\n\n{{C|la|Bodies of water|Landforms}}\n\n==Marau==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mvr|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* ''The Linguistic Situation in the Islands of Yapen, Kurudu, Nau and Miosnum, New Guinea'' (1961)\n\n==Middle Dutch==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|dum|gem-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|dum|odt|*mari|*māri}}, from {{inh|dum|gmw-pro|*mārī}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{dum-adj|head=mâre}}\n\n# [[famous]], [[famed]]\n# [[honoured]], [[prestigious]]\n# [[well]]-[[known]]\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{rfinfl|dum|adjective}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|dum|odt|mari|māri}}, from {{inh|dum|gem-pro|*mēriją}}, related to Etymology 1 above.\n\n====Noun====\n{{dum-noun|head=mâre|f}}\n\n# [[fame]], [[famousness]]\n# [[rumour]]\n# [[message]]\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{dum-decl-noun-wk-f|mâre}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|nl|maar|mare}}\n* {{desc|li|maer}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|dum|odt|*mara}}, from {{inh|dum|gmw-pro|*marā}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{dum-noun|head=māre|f|g2=m}}\n\n# [[#English|mare]], [[nightmare]] (evil spirit)\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{dum-decl-noun-wk-f|māre}}\n{{dum-decl-noun-wk-m|māre}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|nl|maar}}\n* {{desc|li|maar}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:VMNW|ID61572|I}}\n* {{R:VMNW|ID4262|IV}}\n* {{R:VMNW|ID35572|V}}\n* {{R:MNW|28040|I}}\n* {{R:MNW|28041|II}}\n* {{R:MNW|28042|III}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|enm|mare}}\nOriginally two distinct nouns:\n* {{inh|enm|ang|miere}} ({{cog|ang-ang|mære}}, {{m|ang|mere}}), from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*marhijā}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*marhijō}}.\n* {{inh|enm|ang|mearh}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*marh}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*marhaz}}, with the final vowel and semantics of {{m|ang|miere}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|meare||AB}}; {{alter|enm|mure||early|S}}\n* {{alter|enm|meir|mer|meyre||N|NEM}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmaːr(ə)/|qq=from {{m|ang||mear-}}, oblique stem of {{m|ang|mearh}}}}\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmɛ̞ːr(ə)/|qq=from {{m|ang|mere}}}}<!--guaranteed by Chaucer mere:myllere-->\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmyr(ə)/|aa=<<S>>, from {{m|ang-wsx|miere}}}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{enm-noun}}\n\n# A [[horse]] {{gloss|[[member]] of the species {{taxfmt|Equus ferus|species}}}}\n# A {{l|en|mare}} {{gloss|[[female]] [[horse]] or other [[equine]]}}\n# {{lb|enm|derogatory|rare}} A [[woman]] or [[effeminate]] [[man]].\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|mare|id=Q1104034}}\n* {{desc|gmw-msc|meir}}\n** {{desc|sco|meir|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|mēre|n.(1)|1142724264}}\n* {{R:OED Online|mare|<i>n</i>.<sup>1</sup>|noformat=1|8591277143}}\n* {{R:ang:Goering:2025|1-21}}\n* {{R:enm:Zettersten:1965|meare|sb|57}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|enm|spirit}}\n{{inh+|enm|ang|mare||nightmare, monster}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*marā}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*marǭ||nightmare, incubus}}, from {{inh|enm|ine-pro|*mor-||feminine evil spirit}}. \n\nThe form {{m|enm|mere}} is either by analogy with {{m|enm|mere}}, variant of {{m|enm|mare|id=mare|t=horse, mare}} or by confusion with {{m|enm|mere|id=mermaid}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|mere}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmaːr(ə)/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{enm-noun}}\n\n# An [[evil]] [[spirit]] [[believe]]d to be [[active]] during the [[night]].\n#: {{syn|enm|nyghtmare|qq1=non-Northern}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|mare|id=evil spirit}}\n* {{desc|gmw-msc|mare|mair|maire}}\n** {{desc|sco|mare}}\n** {{desc|scz|mare}}\n* {{desc|xno|mare|bor=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|māre|n.(2)|MED26897}}\n* {{R:OED Online|mare|<i>n</i>.<sup>2</sup>|noformat=1|8591277143}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|enm|verb|altform=1}}\n\n# {{lb|enm|Lancs}} {{alt form|enm|merren}}\n\n{{C|enm|Female animals|Horses|Mythological creatures|Night}}\n\n==Munggui==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mth|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* ''The Linguistic Situation in the Islands of Yapen, Kurudu, Nau and Miosnum, New Guinea'' (1961)\n\n==Murui Huitoto==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{huu-IPA}}\n* {{hyph|huu|ma|re}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{huu-class|mare|e}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|huu|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|huu|attributive}} [[good]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{huu-decl-noun}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Root====\n{{head|huu|root}}\n\n# [[good]], [[proper]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|huu\n|maremɨe}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:huu:Burtch:1983|page=173}}\n* {{R:huu:Wojtylak:2017|page=537}}\n\n==Neapolitan==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|nap|la|mare}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nap|/ˈmarə/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|nap|noun|g=?}}\n\n# [[sea]] {{gloss|a vast mass of salty water}}\n\n==Norman==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|nrf|mathe}} {{qualifier|Jersey}}\n* {{l|nrf|mar}} {{qualifier|Sark}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|nrf|fro|mare}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{nrf-noun|f}}\n\n# {{lb|nrf|France|Guernsey}} [[pool]]\n#* {{quote-book|nrf |year=1903 |author=Edgar MacCulloch |title=Guernsey Folk Lore |chapter=Proverbs, Weather Sayings, etc. |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924029911710/page/534/mode/1up?view=theater |page=534 |text=Si le soleil est rouage au sèr, / Ch'est pour biau temps aver, / S'il est rouage au matin, / Ch'est la '''mare''' au chemin. |t=If the sun sets red, it is a sign of fine weather, but when he rises red, you may expect '''pools''' of water on the road.}}\n\n{{topics|nrf|Water}}\n\n==Northern Sotho==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|nso|bnt-pro|*màtáì}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|nso|noun}}\n\n# [[saliva]]\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n{{wp|nb:+ (mytologi)}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|nb|non|mara}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{nb-noun-c}}\n\n# {{lb|nb|folklore}} a {{l|en|mare|id=evil spirit}} {{gloss|an evil spirit}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nb|mareritt||nightmare}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nb|a=aemr|arme|armé|erma}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n{{wp|nn:}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|nn|non|mara|g=f}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|Mara|mara|maru|muru|murru||dialectal}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-f2}}\n\n# {{lb|nn|folklore}} a {{l|en|mare|id=evil spirit}} {{gloss|an evil spirit}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nn|marekors||pentagram}}\n* {{l|nn|marekvist||a witch's broom}}\n* {{l|nn|mareritt||nightmare}}\n* {{l|nn|marespjeld}}\n* {{q|probably derived}} {{l|nn|innmari}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|nn|non|merja||to crush}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|mara||split or a-infinitive}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{nn-verb-1}}\n\n# {{rfdef|nn}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nn|a=aemr|arme|armé|erma|rame|rema}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|ang|gem-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*marā}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|mare}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ang-noun|f|maran}}\n\n# {{l|en|mare}} (evil spirit thought to torment people in their sleep)\n\n====Declension====\n{{ang-decl-noun-n-f|mar}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ang|*nihtmare}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|enm|mare|id=spirit}}\n\n{{topics|ang|Mythological creatures}}\n\n==Old French==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|fro|mar}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|fro|dum|mare||phantom, spirit}}.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{fro-adj|mf}}\n\n# [[evil]]; [[bad]]\n\n===Adverb===\n{{fro-adv}}\n\n# [[evilly]]; [[badly]]\n\n==Pali==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n{{pi-alt}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{pi-verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|pi|marati||s|opt|act|t=to die}}\n\n==Papuma==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ppm|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* ''The Linguistic Situation in the Islands of Yapen, Kurudu, Nau and Miosnum, New Guinea'' (1961)\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|pt|verb form}}\n\n# {{pt-verb form of|marar}}\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ro|/ˈma.re/}}\n* {{audio|ro|LL-Q7913 (ron)-Filosoful-mare.wav}}\n* {{rhymes|ro|are|s=2}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nMost likely [[Appendix:Glossary#inherited|inherited]] from {{inh|ro|la|maiōrem|maiōrem}},<ref>{{cite book |ro|last=Giurgea|first=Ion|year= 2016|title=Limba română, LXV (3)|publisher=Editura Academiei|chapter=Etimologia adjectivului mare. O reconsiderare necesară|url=https://www.diacronia.ro/en/indexing/details/A25724}}</ref> accusative singular of {{inh|ro|la|maior}}, through a [[w:Common Romanian|Common Romanian]] intermediate ''*maure'', akin to {{cog|dlm|maur}}. The shift from /au/ to /a/ is caused by [[Appendix:Glossary#syncope|syncope]]. Compare {{cog|rup|mari}}, {{cog|ruq|mari}}, and the aforementioned {{cog|dlm|maur}}. See also {{cog|pt|mor}}, {{cog|sc-src|mere}} and {{cog|sc-sro|meri}}.<ref>{{cite book |author=Mensching, Guido; Remberger, Eva-Maria|year= 2016|editor=Ledgeway, Adam; Maiden, Martin|title=The Oxford Guide to the Romance Languages|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=278|chapter=Chapter 17: Sardinian|url=https://academic.oup.com/book/9369/chapter-abstract/156215818|isbn=9780199677108}}</ref> This would make the word a {{doublet|ro|maior|nocap=1}} and {{doublet|ro|major|notext=1}}.\n\nFor other examples of this syncope in particular, see {{m+|ro|căta}}, regional variant of {{m+|ro|căuta}}, {{m+|sc|laru}} {{q|dialectal}}, from Latin ''[[laurus#Descendants|laurus]]''; {{m+|fur|fari}}, from Latin ''[[faber#Descendants|faber]]'' (unlike {{m+|lld|faure}}); et cetera.\n\nAn alternative, less likely theory proposes a derivation from {{inh|ro|la|marem}} (“male”), with a semantic shift from ''\"male\"'' to ''\"large\"'', on an [[idiomatic]] basis (i.e. assuming that the expression ''\"s-a făcut mare\"'', meaning ''\"{{q-g|[[third-person singular|3rd-pers. sg.]]}} grew up\"'' [literally \"made themselves big\"] initially referred exclusively to boys becoming men, and that it shifted over time to refer more broadly to physical growth, and by extension, being large). Other theories include a derivation from its [[homonym]] ''mare'' (meaning sea), and a [[substrate]] origin (either [[Proto-Albanian]] or [[Thraco-Dacian]]).\n\n====Adjective====\n{{ro-adj|i}}\n\n# [[big]], [[large]], [[great]]\n#: {{ant|ro|mic}}\n#: {{ux|ro|O mare '''mare'''.|A '''big''' sea.|inline=1}}\n# [[great]], [[mighty]]\n#: {{ux|ro|Un om '''mare'''.|A '''great''' man.|inline=1}}\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{ro-decl-adj|i}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|ro|mări}}\n* {{l|ro|mărime}}\n* {{l|ro|mărinimos}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ro|măreț}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|ro|la|mare}}, from {{inh|ro|itc-pro|*mari}}, from {{inh|ro|ine-pro|*móri}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ro-noun|f|mări}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n#: {{ux|ro|Când am mers la '''mare''', am înotat un pic și mai târziu am prins un pește mare.|When I went to '''sea''', I swam a little and later caught a big fish.}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ro-noun-f-e|mar|măr}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ro|marin}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n{{C|ro|Bodies of water|Landforms}}\n\n==Sardinian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|sc|mari||Campidanese}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|sc|la|mare}}. Compare {{cog|it|mare}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{sc-noun|m|mares}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n\n==Sonsorolese==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|sov|noun}}\n\n# [[boy]]\n\n==Tagalog==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|tl|mars}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clipping|tl|kumare}}, earlier variant of {{m|tl|komadre}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{tl-pr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{tl-noun|b=+}} {{tlb|tl|slang}}\n\n# [[close]] [[female]] [[friend]]; [[sister]]\n#: {{syn|tl|Thesaurus:kaibigan}}\n#: {{coord|tl|brad|pare|tol}}\n#: {{ux|tl|Ano'ng tsika, '''mare'''?|What's the buzz, '''sister'''?}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col|tl|marites|amiga}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Pambansang Diksiyonaryo}}\n* {{R:Tagalog Slang Dictionary}}\n\n==Tahitian==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ty|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|ty|archaic}} [[cough]]\n\n====Usage notes====\nUse {{l|ty|hota}}.\n\n==Ternate==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|tft|/ˈma.ɾe/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{tft-noun}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|tft|mari|t=stone}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:tft:Clercq:1890}}\n\n==Turkish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|tr|bg|мари}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{tr-noun|mareyi|mareler}} {{tlb|tr|dialectal|Dobrich}}\n\n# Used when [[addressing]] a [[female]], usually as an [[intensifier]], but seldom used independently.\n\n==Venda==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|ve|bnt-pro|*màtáì}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ve|noun}}\n\n# [[saliva]]\n\n{{C|ve|Bodily fluids}}\n\n==Venetan==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|vec|/ˈma.ɾe/|a=Venetian}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|vec|la|mater}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|vec|noun|g=f|invariable}}\n\n# [[mother]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|vec|la|mare}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|vec|noun}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n\n==Zazaki==\n{{wp|zza:}}\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|zza|ar|مارا}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{zza-noun|g=mf}}\n\n# [[marriage]]"}}